Action.c(8):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(8):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(8):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(8):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(8):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(8):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br /><br /><strong>Correlation Challenge- Expert\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong>\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n

Action.c(143):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(143):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(143):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(143):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(143):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(143):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(143):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n

Action.c(8):         <div id="head_divStart" style="margin-left: 40px">\r\n
Action.c(8):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(8):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(8):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(8):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(8):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(8):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br /><br /><strong>Correlation Challenge- Expert\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong>\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(8):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(8):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(8):     \n
Action.c(8):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(8):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(8):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(8):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(8):             them.<br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             <strong>Notes</strong>:\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n

Action.c(143):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(143):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(143):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(143):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(143):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(143):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(143):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(143):             <br /><br /><strong>Correlation Challenge- Expert\r\n
Action.c(143):             </strong>\r\n
Action.c(143):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(143):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(143):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(143):     \n
Action.c(143):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(143):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(143):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(143):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(143):             them.<br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             <br />\r\n

Action.c(8):         <div id="head_divStart" style="margin-left: 40px">\r\n
Action.c(8):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(8):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(8):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(8):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(8):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(8):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br /><br /><strong>Correlation Challenge- Expert\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong>\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(8):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(8):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(8):     \n
Action.c(8):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(8):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(8):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(8):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(8):             them.<br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n

Action.c(143):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(143):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(143):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(143):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(143):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(143):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n

Action.c(8):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(8):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(8):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(8):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(8):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(8):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br /><br /><strong>Correlation Challenge- Expert\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong>\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(8):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(8):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(8):     \n
Action.c(8):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(8):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(8):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(8):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(8):             them.<br />\r\n

Action.c(143):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(143):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(143):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(143):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(143):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(143):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(143):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(143):             <br /><br /><strong>Correlation Challenge- Expert\r\n
Action.c(143):             </strong>\r\n
Action.c(143):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(143):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(143):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(143):     \n
Action.c(143):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(143):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(143):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(143):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(143):             them.<br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             <br />\r\n

Action.c(8):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(8):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(8):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(8):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(8):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(8):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br /><br /><strong>Correlation Challenge- Expert\r\n
Action.c(8):             </strong>\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(8):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(8):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(8):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(8):     \n
Action.c(8):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(8):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(8):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(8):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(8):             them.<br />\r\n

Action.c(143):             <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(143):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(143):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(143):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(143):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(143):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(143):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(143):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
